<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-12-09T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-12-09T19:00:00-05:00" n="32" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d32">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">894c.111/16: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Crane</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-12-09T19:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">December 9,
                                        1920—7 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>365. Your 360, November 6, 6 p.m. Department approves your note to the
                            Japanese Minister.</p>
                        <p>Please telegraph whether or not Japanese Legation in its note of April 6,
                                1918,<note n="35" xml:id="d32fn35">Apparently not forwarded to the
                                Department.</note> to the American Legation did not request
                            temporary acquiescence in passport control on South Manchuria
                            Railway.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Davis</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>